Microbiome Data Analysis and Figure Generation

The first step is to load the necessary packages. pacman will install and load any missing packages.

if (!require("pacman")) install.packages("pacman")
Loading required package: pacman
pacman::p_load(decontam, phyloseq, BiocManager, qiime2R, DESeq2, tidyverse, RColorBrewer, viridis, vegan,  ggplot2, patchwork, ggpubr, ranacapa, nlme, compositions, readr, devtools, microViz, ANCOMBC, microbiome, GUniFrac, scales, DT, microshades, dplyr, cowplot)

Use the Qiime2R plugin to import .qza files into a phyloseq object “phy”. Import the rarefied table from Qiime2 that was used to calculate the statistics.

phy = qza_to_phyloseq("core-metrics-results/rarefied_table.qza", "rooted-tree.qza", "taxonomy.qza", "metadata.txt",tmp = "C:/tmp")

Verfiy that all samples have an even read depth.

Ordinations

First, create a phyloseq object that is collapsed to the species level for Jaccard and Bray-Curtis. This is to prevent an artifact from a batching effect from the ASV-calling step.

phy_spe = tax_glom(phy, taxrank = "Species")

Set the colors for to NMDS plots. The first is for Colombia, the second is for the US.

hex_values <- c("#FFCD00", "#396998")

Create the NMDS plots for all four beta diversity distance measures.

phy_jac = ordinate(
  phy_spe, method = "NMDS", distance = "jaccard", binary="TRUE", trymax = 100
  )

Combine the four NMDS plots into a single figure, and create a shared legend and axis titles. Label them with D-G for the final figure. Export it as a .tiff file.

#f1a + f1b + f1c + f1d 

yleft <- text_grob("NMDS 2                                              NMDS 2  ", rot = 90)
bottom <- text_grob("NMDS 1                                                                              NMDS 1          ")


nmds <- { wrap_elements(yleft) +
    {{f1a + f1b + f1c + f1d}} +
    plot_layout(widths = c(1,20)) } /
  bottom +
  plot_layout(heights=c(100,1), guides = "collect") + plot_annotation(tag_levels = list(c(' ', 'D', 'E', 'F', 'G')))                     #optional labeling of individual plots
nmds

ggsave("ordinations.tiff")

Barplot

Now, we’re going to make a taxa barplot using MicroViz. The first step is to remove unknown labels. To find all of the unknown taxa, use the interactive taxa searcher.

tax_fix_interactive(phy)

Edit your phyloseq object using the code from the interactive viewer, and save it as a new phyloseq object.

phy1 <- phy %>%
 tax_fix(
  min_length = 4,
  unknowns = c("Unknown_genus", "Unknown_order", "Unknown_class", "Unknown_family", "Unknown_genus_unclassified", "Unknown_family_unclassified", "unclassified"),
  sep = " ", anon_unique = FALSE,
  suffix_rank = "current"
 )

Set palettes for the barplots, using a single color for a phylum and different shades of the color as different genera within that phylum. We’ll look at the top 5 most abundant phyla, and the top three most abundant genera in each. All genera after those top three will be listed as “other”, so we need a fourth color to represent them. Additionally, all phyla not part of the 5 most abundant will be grouped within an “other” category, which we will represent with various shades of gray.

We will take colors from the microshades package. Start by creating vectors for each color with the shades. By default, microshades lists colors from lightest to darkest, so we will reverse the order using the rev() command. Finally, we’ll combine the lists of colors into a single list. Note that we only have 3 shades of orange. This is because our fourth most abundant phylum, Fusobacteria, only has 3 genera in our dataset, meaning an additional color is not necessary.

#View the default microshades palettes with microshades_cvd_palettes and microshades_palettes

micro_gray <- c("#bdbdbd", "#969696", "#737373", "#525252")
micro_brown <- c("#CAA995", "#B78560", "#9E5C00", "#7D3200")
micro_green <- c("#a1d99b", "#74c476", "#41ab5d", "#238b45")
micro_orange <- c("#fdae6b","#fe9929", "#ff7f00")
micro_blue <- c("#c6dbef", "#9ecae1", "#6baed6", "#4292c6")
micro_purple <- c("#bcbddc", "#9e9ac8", "#807dba", "#6a51a3")

micro_gray <- rev(micro_gray)
micro_brown <- rev(micro_brown)
micro_green <- rev(micro_green)
micro_orange <- rev(micro_orange)
micro_blue <- rev(micro_blue)
micro_purple <- rev(micro_purple)

microcolors <- c(micro_blue, micro_purple, micro_green, micro_orange, micro_brown, micro_gray)

Assign the colors and shades to the appropriate taxa. Note that this command will generate an error message with our specific dataset because we have only 3 members of Fusobacteria. We can ignore it.

hueRank <- "Phylum"
hueRankPlural <- "Phyla"
shadeRank <- "Genus"

# Sort phyloseq at lower, and then higher ranks
pseq2 <-phy1 %>%
  tax_sort(by = sum, at = shadeRank, tree_warn = FALSE) %>%
  tax_sort(by = sum, at = hueRank, tree_warn = FALSE) %>%
  tax_agg(rank = shadeRank)

# Specify number of hues and shades desired
